The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Police on Monday morning recovered the blood-stained clothes of RPF jawan Jiban Ganguly, who has been missing since Friday. The clothes were found near Ratneshwar ghat in Shyamnagar, North 24-Parganas. Following the recovery of the clothes, police searched the river banks and found Ganguly?s torch-light. Ganguly was posted at the Noapara barrack. Divers have been called in to search for the missing jawan.

 Four units of Gouri Shankar Jute Mill, Barrackpore, caught fire on Monday morning. Eight fire extinguishers were immediately pressed into service. Fire brigade personnel, too, rushed to the spot with four fire-tenders and doused the blaze after one-and-a-half hours. 

 Two persons were killed and 15 injured on Monday morning, when a truck ploughed into a marketplace on National Highway 34 at Amdanga, North 24-Parganas, on the city?s northern fringes. Police said the driver of the truck, coming from Barasat, had lost control while speeding past the market. 

 alati Sil, 50, and B. Mondal, 60, were buying flowers when they were knocked down by the truck. Both died on the spot. The injured were admitted to Jawaharlal Nehru Memorial Hospital, Kalyani. 

 A 58-year-old man was killed on Monday morning after a minibus on the Teghoria-Howrah route knocked him down on CR Avenue, in the Burtola area. Police said the accident took place around 10.40 am, when Sahadeb Mandal was crossing the road. The killer bus has been impounded and the driver arrested. 

 The condition of Abhigyan Bose, who set himself on fire at Presidency jail on Thursday, showed signs of improvement on Monday. Doctors attending to him round-the-clock at SSKM Hospital said there was marginal improvement in the convict?s condition. 

 Eight animation films, directed by schoolchildren in the city, were premiered at the childrens section of the 10th Calcutta film festival on Sunday. The films were made by Srijoni Gupta Roy, 9 (Ashok Hall Higher Secondary School); Gabriel Gomes, 13 (Don Bosco Park Circus); Upamanyu Bhattacharya, 10 (Heritage School); Debarati Datta, 13 (Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan); Anupam Goswami, 12 (Shree Bharati School); Sumit Sen, 1 (La Martiniere for Boys); Prianka Chatterjee, 13 (Carmel Convent High School) and Nehal Binani, 8 (Mahadevi Birla Girls? High School).

 The bodies of two men, in their late 20s, were found on a canal bank near Habra, North 24-Parganas, on Monday morning. Police said the bodies had bullet wounds on the back of the heads. 

 Scientists and food experts will come together at a symposium organised by the Ramakrishna Mission, Nimpith, South 24-Parganas, on November 26-27. The participants will delve into sustainable production of safe food from animal and fish origin.

 Mamata Banerjee held a demonstration in front of Tangra police station on Monday to protest the sale of illicit liquor in the area. More than 35 people died over the past week after consuming spurious liquor in the neighbourhood.

